I ran into this bug running a node.js server on a very busy host.  I needed to use a high numbered port that happened to be in the ephemeral port range, and eventually ran into an **EADDRINUSE** error.  When I caught the error and attempted to re-listen, or even exited the worker completely and forked a new one in the parent, it would produce **EADDRINUSE** Ad infinitum.

[*Lots of debugging, strace, and reading the source down to libuv later...*]

In short, once the listen() is passed off to the parent it simply returns the cached fd to the worker regardless if that fd had produced an error.  This is partly due to libuv's delayed bind() error reporting, but there is likely a way to work around this in node.js.

I patched this behavior locally by not caching the fd that produced the error, but for every error produced it leaked fds.  I eventually ran out of time, but thought some core contributor or enterprising engineer might want to take a stab at the correct solution.  In all honesty, the right solution is likely going to need some discussion.

**TO REPRODUCE:**

* bind to port 8001 using **netcat**:

```
# newer netcat
nc -l 8001
# older netcat
netcat -l -p 8001
```

* Start this test server:

```javascript
#!/usr/bin/env node

var net     = require('net');
var cluster = require('cluster');

var workers = 2;
var port    = 8001;

if (cluster.isMaster) {
  for (var i = 0; i < workers; i++) {
    cluster.fork();
  }

  cluster.on('exit', function(worker, code, signal) {
    console.log('worker ' + worker.process.pid + ' died');
    setTimeout(function () { cluster.fork(); }, 2000);
  });

  cluster.on('listening', function(worker, address) {
    console.log('worker ' + worker.process.pid + ' listening');
  });
} else {
  var server = net.createServer(function(c) {
    console.log('worker ' + process.pid + ' got connection');
    c.pipe(c);
  }).listen(port);

  server.on('error', function (err) {
    console.log("[" + process.pid + "] " + JSON.stringify(err));
    process.exit();
